\section{Problem 1}

The attached Python script implements LeNet-5 CNN training using the \texttt{all\_reduce} and \texttt{ring\_all\_reduce} strategies. A benchmark harness evaluates training performance across combinations of \texttt{num\_workers}, \texttt{num\_samples}, and \texttt{num\_epochs}.

\subsection{Base Architecture}
The foundational architecture for the reduction strategies includes:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Multiprocessing \& Pipes:} We use Python's \texttt{multiprocessing} library to spawn independent workers. To simulate distributed memory, inter-process communication is established using the \texttt{Pipe} utility (configured via \texttt{setup\_all\_reduce\_pipes} and \texttt{setup\_ring\_pipes}).
    \item \textbf{Training Loop \& Queue:} A common training function runs per worker, executing the reduction function internally. A \texttt{Queue} is used by the coordinator (worker 0) to return the final model weights to the main script. The queue allows communication from child to parent process.
\end{itemize}

PyTorch is used to initialize the LeNet-5 CNN (from Assignment 2), and Matplotlib is used to plot the benchmarks.

\subsection{All-Reduce}
In this approach, all workers must communicate their local gradients with each other, leading to all-to-all communication. Consequently, the number of communications increases by $\mathcal{O}(n^2)$, where $n$ is the number of workers. We implemented All-Reduce in the following way:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Pipe Dictionary:} We create a dictionary mapping each worker index to a set of $readers$ and $writers$ lists containing unidirectional pipe connections. The $readers$ list grants a worker receive access from all others, while the $writers$ list provides send access, effectively establishing an all-to-all communication network.
    \item \textbf{Gradient Averaging:} Once local gradients are calculated in the training loop, the all-reduce function is called. It broadcasts the local gradient to all workers via the $writers$ pipes and waits to receive the other workers' gradients through the $readers$ pipes.
    \item Finally, the collected gradients are averaged and returned to the training loop.
\end{itemize}

The disadvantage of all-reduce is that it requires a high number of communications and transfers all gradients at once. These large tensors can quickly consume the entire available bandwidth in the communication channel, often overloading it.

\subsection{Ring All-Reduce}
Ring All-Reduce maximizes bandwidth and compute utilization by restricting communication to direct neighbors. This approach makes the communication overhead effectively independent of the number of workers, reducing training time complexity to $\mathcal{O}(n)$. We implemented this as follows:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Pipe Dictionary:} Each worker $i$ uses a unidirectional pipe to send data to worker $(i + 1)$ and receive from worker $(i - 1)$, establishing a ring topology.
    \item \textbf{Flatten Gradients and Chunk:} Because network gradients have varying shapes, they are first flattened into a single 1-D tensor and divided into $N$ equal chunks (where $N$ is the number of workers) to ensure balanced processing.
    \item \textbf{Scatter-Reduce Phase:} Over $N - 1$ cycles, each worker receives a gradient chunk, adds it to its own corresponding chunk, and passes the sum forward. By the end, each worker holds the fully summed values for exactly one chunk.
    \item \textbf{All-Gather Phase:} The fully summed chunks are then circulated around the ring for another $N - 1$ cycles. Once every worker has collected the complete set of summed chunks, they are averaged.
    \item \textbf{Un-Flatten:} The averaged 1-D tensor is iteratively reshaped back into the original gradient tensor dimensions before returning.
\end{itemize}

This process efficiently utilizes available bandwidth to average the gradients, significantly accelerating the reduction.

\subsection{Accuracy and Performance Comparison}
The benchmarks were conducted in two environments:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Laptop:} A smaller benchmark with fewer samples and workers, limited by laptop hardware.
    \item \textbf{Server:} A scaled-up benchmark on a 64-core server, using a much larger number of samples and workers.
    \item \textbf{Common Variables:} In both environments, the epochs were limited to $30$, and the batch size for training was set to $256$.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{Observations}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Floating-Point Variance:} Minor accuracy variations exist between the two methods due to the order of operations in floating-point addition (bulk averaging vs. sequential addition).
    \item \textbf{Resource Utilization:} On the server, All-Reduce capped at roughly 50\% core utilization, whereas Ring All-Reduce successfully achieved 90\% utilization.
    \item \textbf{Scaling Efficiency:} As seen in the performance graphs, All-Reduce slows down significantly as workers are added. Ring All-Reduce yields massive time savings when scaling both workers and samples exponentially.
\end{itemize}

