\section{Problem 3}

In the row-stationary data-flow of the Eyeriss architecture, each processing element (PE) is responsible for processing a specific row of data. To convolve a $3 \times 3$ Input Feature Map (IFMap) with a $2 \times 2$ kernel, we map the operations onto a $2 \times 2$ PE grid. 

The PEs are initialized with the following data:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $PE_{1,1}$: Stores the 1st row of the kernel and the 1st row of the IFMap.
    \item $PE_{1,2}$: Empty.
    \item $PE_{2,1}$: Stores the 2nd row of the kernel and the 2nd row of the IFMap.
    \item $PE_{2,2}$: Stores the 3rd row of the IFMap.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Cycle 1}
$PE_{1,1}$ and $PE_{2,1}$ simultaneously perform multiply-accumulate (MAC) operations to calculate the partial sums (PSums) for the $(1,1)$ position of the Output Feature Map (OFMap). These PSums are added across the columns to compute the final pixel value. 

The OFMap after Cycle 1 is:
\[
\begin{bmatrix} 8 & \_ \\ \_ & \_ \end{bmatrix}
\]

\subsection{Cycle 2}
Only the first column of the PE grid remains active. The kernel values are convolved with the next sequence of IFMap elements to calculate the PSums for the $(1,2)$ position of the OFMap. These are again added across the columns. 

The OFMap after Cycle 2 is:
\[
\begin{bmatrix} 8 & 19 \\ \_ & \_ \end{bmatrix}
\]

\subsection{Cycle 3}
By the end of Cycle 2, processing for the first row of the IFMap is complete. In the PE grid, the kernel data is shifted one column to the right, and the IFMap data is shifted diagonally. 

The updated PE grid states are:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $PE_{1,1}$: Empty.
    \item $PE_{1,2}$: Stores the 1st row of the kernel and the 2nd row of the IFMap.
    \item $PE_{2,1}$: Empty.
    \item $PE_{2,2}$: Stores the 2nd row of the kernel and the 3rd row of the IFMap.
\end{itemize}

Convolution is now performed for the $(2,1)$ element of the OFMap. The PSums are calculated in $PE_{1,2}$ and $PE_{2,2}$ and added together to get the new output.

The OFMap after Cycle 3 is:
\[
\begin{bmatrix} 8 & 19 \\ 16 & \_ \end{bmatrix}
\]

\subsection{Cycle 4}
Similar to Cycle 2, the kernel values convolve with the corresponding IFMap elements to calculate the PSums for the $(2,2)$ position. 

The final OFMap after Cycle 4 is:
\[
\begin{bmatrix} 8 & 19 \\ 16 & 6 \end{bmatrix}
\]

